  53 def _stack(t, length):
  54   """stacks `t` `length` times."""
  55   ones = array_ops.ones_like(array_ops.shape(t))
  56   multiples = array_ops.concat([length, ones], 0)
  57   t = array_ops.tile(array_ops.expand_dims(t, 0), multiples)
  58   return wrap(t, True)

  61 # The following stateful ops can be safely called once, and with the same
  62 # signature as the unconverted version, if their inputs are loop invariant.
  63 # TODO(agarwal): implement a strategy for converting Variable reads/writes. The
  64 # plan is to map each read/write in the loop_fn to a corresponding merged
  65 # read/write in the converted graph. Writes need to be mergeable (e.g.
  66 # AssignAdd) to be used in `pfor`. Given a certain read/write order in the
  67 # loop_fn, doing a one-to-one conversion will simulate executing such
  68 # instructions in lock-step across all iterations.
  69 passthrough_stateful_ops = set([
  70     "VariableV2",
  71     "VarHandleOp",
  72     "ReadVariableOp",
  73     "StackV2",
  74     "TensorArrayWriteV3",
  75     "TensorArrayReadV3",
  76     "TensorArraySizeV3",
  77 ])
  78 
  79 
  80 def _is_stateful_pfor_op(op):
  81   if isinstance(op, WhileOp):
  82     return op.is_stateful
  83   if op.type == "Const":
  84     # Const didn't have an op_def.
  85     return False
  86   if op.type in passthrough_stateful_ops:
  87     return False
  88   assert hasattr(op, "op_def") and op.op_def is not None, op
  89   return op.op_def.is_stateful

  92 # pylint: disable=protected-access
  93 class WhileOp(object):
  94   """Object for storing state for converting the outputs of a while_loop."""
  95 
  96   def __init__(self, exit_node, pfor_ops):
  97     """Initializer.
  98 
  99     Args:
 100       exit_node: A tensor output from the while_loop.
 101       pfor_ops: list of ops inside the current pfor loop.
 102     """
 103     self._pfor_ops = set(pfor_ops)
 104     self._pfor_op_ids = set([x._id for x in pfor_ops])
 105     assert isinstance(exit_node, ops.Tensor)
 106     self._while_context = exit_node.op._get_control_flow_context()
 107     assert isinstance(self._while_context, control_flow_ops.WhileContext)
 108     self._context_name = self._while_context.name
 109     self._condition = self._while_context.pivot.op.inputs[0]
 110     # Parts of an external while_loop could be created inside a pfor loop.
 111     # However for the purpose here, we declare such loops to be external. Also
 112     # note that we check if the condition was created inside or outside to
 113     # determine if the while_loop was first created inside or outside.
 114     # TODO(agarwal): check that the Enter and Exit of this loop are unstacked.
 115     self._is_inside_loop = self.op_is_inside_loop(self._condition.op)
 116     if self._is_inside_loop:
 117       for e in self._while_context.loop_exits:
 118         assert self.op_is_inside_loop(e.op)
 119 
 120     # Note the code below tries to reverse engineer an existing while_loop graph
 121     # by assuming the following pattern of nodes.
 122     #
 123     #          NextIteration <---- Body <--- Enter
 124     #              |                ^
 125     #              V             ___| Y
 126     #    Enter -> Merge -> Switch___
 127     #                       ^       | N
 128     #                       |       V
 129     #                  LoopCond    Exit
 130 
 131     # Node that elements in the list below correspond one-to-one with each
 132     # other. i.e. these lists are the same size, and the i_th entry corresponds
 133     # to different Operations/Tensors of a single cycle as illustrated above.
 134     # List of Switch ops (ops.Operation) that feed into an Exit Node.
 135     self._exit_switches = []
 136     # List of inputs (ops.Tensor) to NextIteration.
 137     self._body_outputs = []
 138     # List of list of control inputs of the NextIteration nodes.
 139     self._next_iter_control_inputs = []
 140     # List of Merge ops (ops.Operation).
 141     self._enter_merges = []
 142     # List of output (ops.Tensor) of Exit nodes.
 143     self._outputs = []
 144 
 145     # List of Enter Tensors.
 146     # There are two types of Enter nodes:
 147     # - The Enter nodes that are used in the `loop_vars` argument to
 148     # `while_loop` (see
 149     # https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/while_loop). We collect
 150     # these Enter nodes immediately below by tracing backwards from the Exit
 151     # nodes via Exit <- Switch <- Merge <- Enter. You can see this chain in the
 152     # diagram above. This allows us to have a 1:1 correspondence between the
 153     # self._outputs and the first elements in self._enters.
 154     # - The Enter nodes that are used only by the body. They don't appear in the
 155     # `loop_vars` and are not returned from the `while_loop`. In Python code,
 156     # they are usually captured by the body lambda. We collect them below by
 157     # iterating over all the ops in the graph. They are appended to the end of
 158     # self._enters or self._direct_enters, and don't correspond to any outputs
 159     # in self._outputs. Note that we keep the resource/variant Enter nodes in
 160     # self._direct_enters and the constructed while_loop's body uses them
 161     # directly as opposed to passing them as loop variables. This is done
 162     # because the while_body cannot partition the resource/variant Tensors, so
 163     # it has to leave them unchanged.
 164     self._enters = []
 165     self._direct_enters = []
 166 
 167     for e in self._while_context.loop_exits:
 168       self._outputs.append(e.op.outputs[0])
 169       switch = e.op.inputs[0].op
 170       assert switch.type == "Switch", switch
 171       self._exit_switches.append(switch)
 172       merge = switch.inputs[0].op
 173       assert merge.type == "Merge", merge
 174       self._enter_merges.append(merge)
 175       enter = merge.inputs[0].op
 176       assert enter.type == "Enter", enter
 177       self._enters.append(enter.outputs[0])
 178       next_iter = merge.inputs[1].op
 179       assert next_iter.type == "NextIteration", next_iter
 180       self._body_outputs.append(next_iter.inputs[0])
 181       self._next_iter_control_inputs.append(next_iter.control_inputs)
 182 
 183     # Collect all the Enter nodes that are not part of `loop_vars`, the second
 184     # category described above.
 185     # Also track whether the loop body has any stateful ops.
 186     self._is_stateful = False
 187     for op in ops.get_default_graph().get_operations():
 188       # TODO(agarwal): make sure this works with nested case.
 189       control_flow_context = op._get_control_flow_context()
 190       if control_flow_context is None:
 191         continue
 192       if control_flow_context.name == self._context_name:
 193         self._is_stateful |= _is_stateful_pfor_op(op)
 194         if op.type == "Enter":
 195           output = op.outputs[0]
 196           if output not in self._enters:
 197             if output.dtype in (dtypes.resource, dtypes.variant):
 198               if output not in self._direct_enters:
 199                 self._direct_enters.append(output)
 200             else:
 201               self._enters.append(output)
 202 
 203   def __str__(self):
 204     """String representation."""
 205     return "while_loop(%s)" % self.name
 206 
 207   @property
 208   def inputs(self):
 209     """Input to all the Enter nodes."""
 210     return [x.op.inputs[0] for x in self._enters + self._direct_enters]
 211 
 212   @property
 213   def control_inputs(self):
 214     """Control input to all the Enter nodes."""
 215     control_inputs = []
 216     for x in self._enters + self._direct_enters:
 217       control_inputs.extend(x.op.control_inputs)
 218     return control_inputs
 219 
 220   @property
 221   def outputs(self):
 222     """Outputs of all the Exit nodes."""
 223     return self._outputs
 224 
 225   @property
 226   def name(self):
 227     """Context name for the while loop."""
 228     return self._context_name
 229 
 230   @property
 231   def is_inside_loop(self):
 232     """Returns true if the while_loop was created inside the pfor."""
 233     return self._is_inside_loop
 234 
 235   def op_is_inside_loop(self, op):
 236     """True if op was created inside the pfor loop body."""
 237     assert isinstance(op, ops.Operation)
 238     # Note that we use self._pfor_op_ids for the check and not self._pfor_ops
 239     # since it appears there tensorflow API could return different python
 240     # objects representing the same Operation node.
 241     return op._id in self._pfor_op_ids
 242 
 243   @property
 244   def is_stateful(self):
 245     return self._is_stateful
 246 
 247   @property
 248   def pfor_converter(self):
 249     """Return a converter for the while loop."""
 250     return self
 251 
 252   def _init_pfor(self, parent_pfor, indices, cond_stacked, inputs,
 253                  inputs_stacked):
 254     """Create a PFor object for converting parts of the while_loop.
 255 
 256     Args:
 257       parent_pfor: PFor object being used for converting the while_loop.
 258       indices: int32 Tensor of ids for the iterations that are still active
 259         (i.e. did not exit the while_loop).
 260       cond_stacked: True if the while_loop condition is stacked.
 261       inputs: list of input Tensors corresponding 1-to-1 with self._enters. Note
 262         that these Tensors are a subset of the loop variables for the generated
 263         while_loop.
 264       inputs_stacked: List of booleans corresponding 1-to-1 with `inputs`,
 265         indicating if the value is stacked or not.
 266 
 267     Returns:
 268       A PFor instance. The instance is initialized by adding conversion mappings
 269         of nodes that will be external to the conversion that the returned
 270         instance will be used for. e.g. Enter nodes as well as Merge and Switch
 271         outputs are mapped to converted values.
 272     """
 273     num_outputs = len(self._outputs)
 274     assert len(inputs) == len(self._enters)
 275     assert len(inputs_stacked) == len(self._enters)
 276     loop_var = parent_pfor.loop_var
 277     loop_len = array_ops.size(indices)
 278     pfor = PFor(
 279         loop_var,
 280         loop_len,
 281         pfor_ops=self._pfor_ops,
 282         all_indices=indices,
 283         all_indices_partitioned=cond_stacked)
 284     # Map all inputs of Enter nodes in self._direct_enters to their converted
 285     # values.
 286     for enter in self._direct_enters:
 287       enter_input = enter.op.inputs[0]
 288       converted_enter, stacked, is_sparse_stacked = parent_pfor._convert_helper(
 289           enter_input)
 290       # Since these are resources / variants, they should be unstacked.
 291       assert not stacked and not is_sparse_stacked, (enter, converted_enter)
 292       pfor._add_conversion(enter, wrap(converted_enter, False))
 293 
 294     # Map all Enter nodes to the inputs.
 295     for enter, inp, stacked in zip(self._enters, inputs, inputs_stacked):
 296       pfor._add_conversion(enter, wrap(inp, stacked))
 297     # Map outputs of Switch and Merge.
 298     for i in range(num_outputs):
 299       wrapped_inp = wrap(inputs[i], inputs_stacked[i])
 300       merge = self._enter_merges[i]
 301       pfor._add_conversion(merge.outputs[0], wrapped_inp)
 302       # Note that second output of Merge is typically not used, except possibly
 303       # as a control dependency. To avoid trying to output the correct value, we
 304       # employ a hack here. We output a dummy invalid value with an incorrect
 305       # dtype. This will allow control dependency to work but if using it as an
 306       # input, it should typically lead to errors during graph construction due
 307       # to dtype mismatch.
 308       # TODO(agarwal): Check in the original graph to see if there are any
 309       # consumers of this Tensor that use it as an input.
 310       pfor._add_conversion(merge.outputs[1],
 311                            wrap(constant_op.constant(-1.0), False))
 312       switch = self._exit_switches[i]
 313       # Don't need to worry about switch.output[0] which will feed to Exit node.
 314       pfor._add_conversion(switch.outputs[1], wrapped_inp)
 315     return pfor
 316 
 317   def _convert_enter(self, parent_pfor, enter):
 318     """Converts an Enter node."""
 319     inp, stacked, _ = parent_pfor._convert_helper(enter.op.inputs[0])
 320     control_inputs = [
 321         parent_pfor._convert_helper(x).t for x in enter.op.control_inputs
 322     ]
 323     if control_inputs:
 324       with ops.control_dependencies(control_inputs):
 325         inp = array_ops.identity(inp)
 326     return inp, stacked
 327 
 328   def _maybe_stacked(self, cache, inp):
 329     """Heuristic to figue out if the coverting inp leads to a stacked value.
 330 
 331 
 332     Args:
 333       cache: map from Tensor to boolean indicating stacked/unstacked.
 334       inp: input Tensor.
 335 
 336     Returns:
 337       True if `inp` could get stacked. If the function returns False, the
 338       converted value should be guaranteed to be unstacked. If returning True,
 339       it may or may not be stacked.
 340     """
 341     if inp in cache:
 342       return cache[inp]
 343     if not self.op_is_inside_loop(inp.op):
 344       return False
 345     op = inp.op
 346     output = False
 347     if op.type in [
 348         "Shape",
 349         "Rank"
 350         "ShapeN",
 351         "ZerosLike",
 352         "TensorArrayV3",
 353         "TensorArraySizeV3",
 354     ]:
 355       output = False
 356     elif _is_stateful_pfor_op(op):
 357       # This may be fairly aggressive.
 358       output = True
 359     elif op.type == "Exit":
 360       # This may be fairly aggressive.
 361       output = True
 362     else:
 363       for t in op.inputs:
 364         if self._maybe_stacked(cache, t):
 365           output = True
 366           break
 367     cache[inp] = output
 368     return output
 369 
 370   def _create_init_values(self, pfor_input):
 371     """Create arguments passed to converted while_loop."""
 372     with ops.name_scope("while_init"):
 373       loop_len_vector = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
 374       loop_len = loop_len_vector[0]
 375       num_outputs = len(self._outputs)
 376 
 377       inputs = []
 378       maybe_stacked_cache = {}
 379       # Convert all the Enters. Need to do this before checking for stacking
 380       # below.
 381       for i, enter in enumerate(self._enters):
 382         inp, stacked = self._convert_enter(pfor_input.pfor, enter)
 383         inputs.append(inp)
 384         maybe_stacked_cache[enter] = stacked
 385         # Since this enter node is part of the `loop_vars`, it corresponds to an
 386         # output and its preceding switch. We mark this switch's output the same
 387         # stackness, to act at the base case for the logic below. Below, we will
 388         # be going through the body figuring out which inputs might need to be
 389         # stacked and which inputs can safely remain unstacked.
 390         if i < num_outputs:
 391           maybe_stacked_cache[self._exit_switches[i].outputs[1]] = stacked
 392 
 393       # Shape invariants for init_values corresponding to self._enters.
 394       input_shape_invariants = []
 395       # TensorArrays for outputs of converted while loop
 396       output_tas = []
 397       # Shape invariants for output TensorArrays.
 398       ta_shape_invariants = []
 399       # List of booleans indicating stackness of inputs, i.e. tensors
 400       # corresponding to self._enters.
 401       inputs_stacked = []
 402       for i, inp in enumerate(inputs):
 403         enter = self._enters[i]
 404         inp_stacked = self._maybe_stacked(maybe_stacked_cache, enter)
 405         # Note that even when an input is unstacked, the body could make it
 406         # stacked. we use a heuristic below to figure out if body may be making
 407         # it stacked.
 408         if i < num_outputs:
 409           body_output = self._body_outputs[i]
 410           if enter.op in self._pfor_ops:
 411             body_output_stacked = self._maybe_stacked(maybe_stacked_cache,
 412                                                       body_output)
 413           else:
 414             # If constructed outside of pfor loop, then the output would not be
 415             # stacked.
 416             body_output_stacked = False
 417           if body_output_stacked and not inp_stacked:
 418             inp = _stack(inp, loop_len_vector).t
 419             inputs[i] = inp
 420             inp_stacked = True
 421           # TODO(agarwal): other attributes for the TensorArray ?
 422           output_tas.append(tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(inp.dtype, loop_len))
 423           ta_shape_invariants.append(tensor_shape.TensorShape(None))
 424 
 425         inputs_stacked.append(inp_stacked)
 426         input_shape_invariants.append(tensor_shape.TensorShape(None))
 427 
 428       # See documentation for __call__ for the structure of init_values.
 429       init_values = [True, pfor_input.pfor.all_indices] + inputs + output_tas
 430       # TODO(agarwal): try stricter shape invariants
 431       shape_invariants = (
 432           [tensor_shape.TensorShape(None),
 433            tensor_shape.TensorShape(None)
 434           ] + input_shape_invariants + ta_shape_invariants)
 435 
 436       return init_values, inputs_stacked, shape_invariants
 437 
 438   def _process_cond_unstacked(self, conditions, indices, inputs, output_tas):
 439     """Handles case when condition is unstacked.
 440 
 441     Note that all iterations end together. So we don't need to partition the
 442     inputs. When all iterations are done, we write the inputs to the
 443     TensorArrays. Note that we only write to index 0 of output_tas. Since all
 444     iterations end together, they can all be output together.
 445     """
 446     not_all_done = array_ops.reshape(conditions, [])
 447     new_output_tas = []
 448     # pylint: disable=cell-var-from-loop
 449     for i, out_ta in enumerate(output_tas):
 450       inp = inputs[i]
 451       new_output_tas.append(
 452           control_flow_ops.cond(not_all_done,
 453                                 lambda: out_ta,
 454                                 lambda: out_ta.write(0, inp)))
 455     # pylint: enable=cell-var-from-loop
 456     return not_all_done, indices, inputs, new_output_tas
 457 
 458   def _process_cond_stacked(self, conditions, indices, inputs, inputs_stacked,
 459                             output_tas):
 460     num_outputs = len(self._outputs)
 461     # Compute if all iterations are done.
 462     not_all_done = math_ops.reduce_any(conditions)
 463     conditions_int = math_ops.cast(conditions, dtypes.int32)
 464     # Partition the indices.
 465     done_indices, new_indices = data_flow_ops.dynamic_partition(
 466         indices, conditions_int, 2)
 467 
 468     new_inputs = []
 469     new_output_tas = []
 470     for i, (inp, stacked) in enumerate(zip(inputs, inputs_stacked)):
 471       # Partition the inputs.
 472       if stacked:
 473         done_inp, new_inp = data_flow_ops.dynamic_partition(
 474             inp, conditions_int, 2)
 475       else:
 476         # TODO(agarwal): avoid this stacking. See TODO earlier in
 477         # _process_cond_unstacked.
 478         done_inp = _stack(inp, [array_ops.size(done_indices)]).t
 479         new_inp = inp
 480       new_inputs.append(new_inp)
 481       # For iterations that are done, write them to TensorArrays.
 482       if i < num_outputs:
 483         out_ta = output_tas[i]
 484         # Note that done_indices can be empty. done_inp should also be empty in
 485         # that case.
 486         new_output_tas.append(out_ta.scatter(done_indices, done_inp))
 487     return not_all_done, new_indices, new_inputs, new_output_tas
 488 
 489   def _process_body(self, pfor_input, inputs_stacked,
 490                     new_indices, cond_stacked, new_inputs,
 491                     not_all_done):
 492     """Convert the body function."""
 493 
 494     def true_fn(control_inputs, body_pfor, body_output, stacked):
 495       """Converts the body function for all but last iteration.
 496 
 497       This essentially converts body_output. Additionally, it needs to handle
 498       any control dependencies on the NextIteration node. So it creates another
 499       Identity node with the converted dependencies.
 500       """
 501       converted_control_inp = []
 502       for x in control_inputs:
 503         for t in x.outputs:
 504           converted_control_inp.append(body_pfor._convert_helper(t).t)
 505       if stacked:
 506         # Note convert always does the stacking.
 507         output = body_pfor.convert(body_output)
 508       else:
 509         output, convert_stacked, _ = body_pfor._convert_helper(body_output)
 510         assert convert_stacked == stacked, body_output
 511       with ops.control_dependencies(converted_control_inp):
 512         return array_ops.identity(output)
 513 
 514     body_pfor = self._init_pfor(pfor_input.pfor, new_indices,
 515                                 cond_stacked, new_inputs,
 516                                 inputs_stacked)
 517     new_outputs = []
 518 
 519     for i, (body_output, stacked) in enumerate(
 520         zip(self._body_outputs, inputs_stacked)):
 521       control_inp = self._next_iter_control_inputs[i]
 522       out_dtype = body_output.dtype
 523       # Note that we want to run the body only if not all pfor iterations are
 524       # done. If all are done, we return empty tensors since these values will
 525       # not be used. Notice that the value returned by the loop is based on
 526       # TensorArrays and not directly on these returned values.
 527       # pylint: disable=cell-var-from-loop
 528       new_output = control_flow_ops.cond(
 529           not_all_done,
 530           lambda: true_fn(control_inp, body_pfor, body_output, stacked),
 531           lambda: constant_op.constant([], dtype=out_dtype))
 532       # pylint: enable=cell-var-from-loop
 533       new_outputs.append(new_output)
 534     return new_outputs
 535 
 536   def __call__(self, pfor_input):
 537     """Converter for the while_loop.
 538 
 539     The conversion of a while_loop is another while_loop.
 540 
 541     The arguments to this converted while_loop are as follows:
 542     not_all_done: Boolean scalar Tensor indicating if all the pfor iterations
 543       are done.
 544     indices: int32 1-D Tensor storing the id of the iterations that are not
 545       done.
 546     args: Remaining arguments. These can be divided into 3 categories:
 547       - First set of arguments are the tensors that correspond to the initial
 548         elements of self._enters. The elements that appear in original while
 549         loop's `loop_vars`.
 550       - The second set of arguments are the tensors that correspond to the
 551         remaining elements of self._enters. These are the tensors that directly
 552         enter the original while loop body.
 553        - Finally, the last set of arguments are TensorArrays. These TensorArrays
 554          correspond to the outputs of the original while_loop, i.e. to the
 555          elements in self._outputs. Each TensorArray has `PFor.loop_len`
 556          elements, i.e. the number of pfor iterations. At the end, the i'th
 557          element of each TensorArray will contain the output computed by the
 558          i'th iteration of pfor. Note that elements can be written into these
 559          tensors arrays in any order, depending on when the corresponding pfor
 560          iteration is done.
 561       If the original while_loop had `k` tensors in its `loop_vars` and its body
 562       directly captured `m` tensors, the `args` will contain `2 * k + m` values.
 563 
 564     In each iteration, the while_loop body recomputes the condition for all
 565     active pfor iterations to see which of them are now done. It then partitions
 566     all the inputs and passes them along to the converted body. Values for all
 567     the iterations that are done are written to TensorArrays indexed by the pfor
 568     iteration number. When all iterations are done, the TensorArrays are stacked
 569     to get the final value.
 570 
 571     Args:
 572       pfor_input: A PForInput object corresponding to the output of any Exit
 573         node from this while loop.
 574 
 575     Returns:
 576       List of converted outputs.
 577     """
 578     # Create init_values that will be passed to the while_loop.
 579     init_values, inputs_stacked, shape_invariants = self._create_init_values(
 580         pfor_input)
 581     # Note that we use a list as a hack since we need the nested function body
 582     # to set the value of cond_is_stacked. python2.x doesn't support nonlocal
 583     # variables.
 584     cond_is_stacked = [None]
 585 
 586     def cond(not_all_done, *_):
 587       return not_all_done
 588 
 589     def body(not_all_done, indices, *args):
 590       # See documentatin for __call__ for the structure of *args.
 591       num_enters = len(self._enters)
 592       inputs = args[:num_enters]
 593       output_tas = args[num_enters:]
 594       # TODO(agarwal): see which outputs have consumers and only populate the
 595       # TensorArrays corresponding to those. Or do those paths get trimmed out
 596       # from inside the while_loop body?
 597       assert len(inputs) >= len(output_tas)
 598       assert len(inputs) == len(inputs_stacked)
 599 
 600       # Convert condition
 601       with ops.name_scope("while_cond"):
 602         # Note that we set cond_stacked to True here. At this point we don't
 603         # know if it could be loop invariant, hence the conservative value is
 604         # to assume stacked.
 605         cond_pfor = self._init_pfor(pfor_input.pfor, indices,
 606                                     cond_stacked=True,
 607                                     inputs=inputs,
 608                                     inputs_stacked=inputs_stacked)
 609         conditions, cond_stacked, _ = cond_pfor._convert_helper(self._condition)
 610         cond_is_stacked[0] = cond_stacked
 611 
 612       # Recompute the new condition, write outputs of done iterations, and
 613       # partition the inputs if needed.
 614       if not cond_stacked:
 615         (not_all_done, new_indices,
 616          new_inputs, new_output_tas) = self._process_cond_unstacked(
 617              conditions, indices, inputs, output_tas)
 618       else:
 619         (not_all_done, new_indices,
 620          new_inputs, new_output_tas) = self._process_cond_stacked(
 621              conditions, indices, inputs, inputs_stacked, output_tas)
 622 
 623       # Convert body
 624       with ops.name_scope("while_body"):
 625         #  Compute the outputs from the body.
 626         new_outputs = self._process_body(pfor_input, inputs_stacked,
 627                                          new_indices, cond_stacked, new_inputs,
 628                                          not_all_done)
 629 
 630       # Note that the first num_outputs new values of inputs are computed using
 631       # the body. Rest of them were direct Enters into the condition/body and
 632       # the partitioning done earlier is sufficient to give the new value.
 633       num_outputs = len(self._outputs)
 634       new_args = ([not_all_done, new_indices] + new_outputs + list(
 635           new_inputs[num_outputs:]) + new_output_tas)
 636       return tuple(new_args)
 637 
 638     while_outputs = control_flow_ops.while_loop(
 639         cond, body, init_values, shape_invariants=shape_invariants)
 640     output_tas = while_outputs[-len(self._outputs):]
 641     outputs = []
 642     assert cond_is_stacked[0] is not None
 643     for inp_stacked, ta in zip(inputs_stacked, output_tas):
 644       if cond_is_stacked[0]:
 645         outputs.append(wrap(ta.stack(), True))
 646       else:
 647         # Note that if while_loop condition is unstacked, all iterations exit at
 648         # the same time and we wrote those outputs in index 0 of the tensor
 649         # array.
 650         outputs.append(wrap(ta.read(0), inp_stacked))
 651     return outputs
 652

 654 class _PforInput(object):
 655   """Input object passed to registered pfor converters."""
 656 
 657   def __init__(self, pfor, op, inputs):
 658     """Creates a _PforInput object.
 659 
 660     Args:
 661       pfor: PFor converter object.
 662       op: the Operation object that is being converted.
 663       inputs: list of WrappedTensor objects representing converted values of the
 664         inputs of `op`.
 665     """
 666     self.pfor = pfor
 667     self._op = op
 668     self._inputs = inputs
 669 
 670   def stack_inputs(self, stack_indices=None):
 671     """Stacks unstacked inputs at `stack_indices`.
 672 
 673     Args:
 674       stack_indices: indices of inputs at which stacking is done. If None,
 675         stacking is done at all indices.
 676     """
 677     if stack_indices is None:
 678       stack_indices = range(len(self._inputs))
 679     length = self.pfor.loop_len_vector
 680     for i in stack_indices:
 681       inp = self._inputs[i]
 682       if not inp.is_stacked:
 683         self._inputs[i] = _stack(inp.t, length)
 684 
 685   def expanddim_inputs_for_broadcast(self):
 686     """Reshapes stacked inputs to prepare them for broadcast.
 687 
 688     Since stacked inputs have an extra leading dimension, automatic broadcasting
 689     rules could incorrectly try to expand dimensions before that leading
 690     dimension. To avoid that, we reshape these stacked inputs to the maximum
 691     rank they will need to be broadcasted to.
 692     """
 693     if not self._inputs:
 694       return
 695 
 696     # Find max rank
 697     def _get_rank(x):
 698       rank = array_ops.rank(x.t)
 699       if not x.is_stacked:
 700         rank += 1
 701       return rank
 702 
 703     ranks = [_get_rank(x) for x in self._inputs]
 704     max_rank = ranks[0]
 705     for rank in ranks[1:]:
 706       max_rank = math_ops.maximum(rank, max_rank)
 707 
 708     for i, inp in enumerate(self._inputs):
 709       if inp.is_stacked:
 710         shape = array_ops.shape(inp.t)
 711         rank_diff = array_ops.reshape(max_rank - ranks[i], [1])
 712         ones = array_ops.tile([1], rank_diff)
 713         new_shape = array_ops.concat([shape[:1], ones, shape[1:]], axis=0)
 714         self._inputs[i] = wrap(array_ops.reshape(inp.t, new_shape), True)
 715 
 716   @property
 717   def inputs(self):
 718     return self._inputs
 719 
 720   @property
 721   def num_inputs(self):
 722     return len(self._inputs)
 723 
 724   def input(self, index):
 725     assert len(self._inputs) > index, (index, self._inputs)
 726     return self._inputs[index]
 727 
 728   def stacked_input(self, index):
 729     t, is_stacked, _ = self.input(index)
 730     if not is_stacked:
 731       op_type = self.op_type
 732       op_def = getattr(self._op, "op_def", None)
 733       if op_def is None:
 734         input_name = "at index %d" % index
 735       else:
 736         input_name = "\"%s\"" % op_def.input_arg[index].name
 737       raise ValueError("Input %s of op \"%s\" expected to be not loop invariant"
 738                        ".\nError while converting op %s"
 739                        "with converted inputs\n%s" % (input_name, op_type,
 740                                                       self._op, self.inputs))
 741     return t
 742 
 743   def unstacked_input(self, index):
 744     t, is_stacked, _ = self.input(index)
 745     if is_stacked:
 746       op_type = self.op_type
 747       op_def = getattr(self._op, "op_def", None)
 748       if op_def is None:
 749         input_name = "at index %d" % index
 750       else:
 751         input_name = "\"%s\"" % op_def.input_arg[index].name
 752       raise ValueError("Input %s of op \"%s\" expected to be loop invariant"
 753                        ".\nError while converting op %s"
 754                        "with converted inputs\n%s" % (input_name, op_type,
 755                                                       self._op, self.inputs))
 756     return t

 760     return self._op

 764     return self._op.type

 767     return self._op.get_attr(attr)

 770   def outputs(self):
 771     return self._op.outputs

 774     assert index < len(self._op.outputs)
 775     return self._op.outputs[index]

 781 class RegisterPFor(object):
 782   """Utility to register converters for pfor.
 783 
 784   Usage:
 785   @RegisterPFor(foo_op_type)
 786   def _foo_converter(pfor_input):
 787     ...
 788 
 789   The above will register conversion function `_foo_converter` for handling
 790   conversion of `foo_op_type`. During conversion, the registered functin will be
 791   called with a single argument of type `PForInput` which will contain state
 792   needed for the conversion.  This registered function should output a list of
 793   WrappedTensor object with the same length as the number of outputs of op being
 794   converted. If the op had zero outputs, then it should return a ops.Operation
 795   object.
 796   """
 797 
 798   def __init__(self, op_type):
 799     """Creates an object to register a converter for op with type `op_type`."""
 800     self.op_type = op_type
 801 
 802   def __call__(self, converter):
 803     name = self.op_type
 804     assert name not in _pfor_converter_registry, "Re-registering %s " % name
 805     _pfor_converter_registry[name] = converter
 806     return converter
 807

 809 class RegisterPForWithArgs(RegisterPFor):
 810   """Utility to register converters for pfor.
 811 
 812   Usage:
 813   @RegisteRPFor(foo_op_type, foo=value, ....)
 814   def _foo_converter(pfor_input, foo=None, ....):
 815     ...
 816 
 817   See RegisterPFor for details on the conversion function.
 818   `RegisterPForWithArgs` allows binding extra arguments to the
 819   conversion function at registration time.
 820   """
 821 
 822   def __init__(self, op_type, *args, **kw_args):
 823     super(RegisterPForWithArgs, self).__init__(op_type)
 824     self._args = args
 825     self._kw_args = kw_args
 826 
 827   def __call__(self, converter):
 828 
 829     def _f(pfor_input):
 830       return converter(pfor_input, self.op_type, *self._args, **self._kw_args)
 831 
 832     super(RegisterPForWithArgs, self).__call__(_f)
 833     return converter

 842 WrappedTensor = collections.namedtuple("WrappedTensor",
 843                                        ["t", "is_stacked", "is_sparse_stacked"])
 844 """Wrapper around the result of a Tensor conversion.
 845 
 846 The additional fields are useful for keeping track of the conversion state as
 847 data flows through the ops in the loop body. For every op whose output is a
 848 Tensor, its converter should return either a WrappedTensor or a list of
 849 WrappedTensors.
 850 
 851 Args:
 852   t: The converted tensor
 853   is_stacked: True if the tensor is stacked, i.e. represents the results of all
 854     the iterations of the loop, where each row i of the tensor corresponds to
 855     that op's output on iteration i of the loop. False if the tensor is not
 856     stacked, i.e. represents the result of the op on of a single iteration of
 857     the loop, where the result does not vary between iterations.
 858   is_sparse_stacked: True if the tensor corresponds to a component tensor
 859     (indices, values, or dense_shape) of a sparse tensor, and has been logically
 860     stacked via a sparse conversion.
 861 """
 862 
 863 
 864 def wrap(tensor, is_stacked=True, is_sparse_stacked=False):
 865   """Helper to create a WrappedTensor object."""
 866   assert isinstance(is_stacked, bool)
 867   assert isinstance(is_sparse_stacked, bool)
 868   assert isinstance(tensor, ops.Tensor)
 869   assert not is_sparse_stacked or is_stacked, ("If the wrapped tensor is "
 870                                                "stacked via a sparse "
 871                                                "conversion, it must also be "
 872                                                "stacked.")
 873   return WrappedTensor(tensor, is_stacked, is_sparse_stacked)
 874 
 875 
 876 def _fallback_converter(pfor_input):
 877   logging.warn("Using a while_loop for converting %s", pfor_input.op_type)
 878   output_dtypes = [x.dtype for x in pfor_input.outputs]
 879   iters = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector[0]
 880 
 881   def while_body(i, *ta_list):
 882     """Body of while loop."""
 883     inputs = [
 884         x[i, ...] if stacked else x for x, stacked, _ in pfor_input.inputs
 885     ]
 886     op_outputs = _create_op(
 887         pfor_input.op_type,
 888         inputs,
 889         output_dtypes,
 890         attrs=pfor_input.op.node_def.attr).outputs
 891 
 892     outputs = []
 893     for out, ta in zip(op_outputs, ta_list):
 894       assert isinstance(out, ops.Tensor)
 895       outputs.append(ta.write(i, array_ops.expand_dims(out, 0)))
 896     return tuple([i + 1] + outputs)
 897 
 898   ta_list = control_flow_ops.while_loop(
 899       lambda i, *ta: i < iters, while_body, [0] + [
 900           tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(dtype, iters) for dtype in output_dtypes
 901       ])[1:]
 902   return tuple([wrap(ta.concat(), True) for ta in ta_list])

 905 class PFor(object):
 906   """Implementation of rewrite of parallel-for loops.
 907 
 908   This class takes a DAG or a set of DAGs representing the body of a
 909   parallel-for loop, and adds new operations to the graph that implements
 910   functionality equivalent to running that loop body for a specified number of
 911   iterations. This new set of nodes may or may not use a tensorflow loop
 912   construct.
 913 
 914   The process of conversion does not delete or change any existing operations.
 915   It only adds operations that efficiently implement the equivalent
 916   functionality. We refer to the added ops as "converted ops".
 917 
 918   The conversion process uses a simple greedy heuristic. It walks the loop body
 919   and tries to express the functionality of running each node in a loop with a
 920   new set of nodes. When converting an op several cases are possible:
 921   - The op is not inside the loop body. Hence it can be used as is.
 922   - The op does not depend on the iteration number and is stateless. In this
 923     case, it can be used as is.
 924   - The op is not stateful, and depends on iteration number only through control
 925     dependencies. In this case, we can create a single op with same inputs and
 926     attributes, but with "converted" control dependencies.
 927   - The op is not stateful, and all its inputs are loop invariant. In this
 928     case, similar to above, we can create a single op with same inputs and
 929     attributes, but with "converted" control dependencies.
 930   - The op is stateful or at least one of the inputs is not loop invariant. In
 931     this case, we run the registered converter for that op to create a set of
 932     converted ops. All nodes in the set will have converted control dependencies
 933     corresponding to control dependencies of the original op. If the op returned
 934     multiple outputs, "converted outputs" could be produced by different ops in
 935     this set.
 936   """
 937 
 938   def __init__(self,
 939                loop_var,
 940                loop_len,
 941                pfor_ops,
 942                all_indices=None,
 943                all_indices_partitioned=False):
 944     """Creates an object to rewrite a parallel-for loop.
 945 
 946     Args:
 947       loop_var: ops.Tensor output of a Placeholder operation. The value should
 948         be an int32 scalar representing the loop iteration number.
 949       loop_len: A scalar or scalar Tensor representing the number of iterations
 950         the loop is run for.
 951       pfor_ops: List of all ops inside the loop body.
 952       all_indices: If not None, an int32 vector with size `loop_len`
 953         representing the iteration ids that are still active. These values
 954         should be unique and sorted. However they may not be contiguous. This is
 955         typically the case when inside a control flow construct which has
 956         partitioned the indices of the iterations that are being converted.
 957       all_indices_partitioned: If True, this object is being constructed from a
 958        control flow construct where not all the pfor iterations are guaranteed
 959        to be active.
 960     """
 961     assert isinstance(loop_var, ops.Tensor)
 962     assert loop_var.op.type == "Placeholder"
 963     self._loop_var = loop_var
 964     loop_len_value = tensor_util.constant_value(loop_len)
 965     if loop_len_value is not None:
 966       loop_len = loop_len_value
 967     self._loop_len_vector = array_ops.reshape(loop_len, [1])
 968     self._all_indices_partitioned = all_indices_partitioned
 969     if all_indices_partitioned:
 970       assert all_indices is not None
 971     self.all_indices = (
 972         math_ops.range(loop_len) if all_indices is None else all_indices)
 973 
 974     self._conversion_map = {}
 975     self._conversion_map[loop_var] = wrap(self.all_indices, True)
 976     self._pfor_ops = set(pfor_ops)
 977     self._pfor_op_ids = set([x._id for x in pfor_ops])
 978 
 979   def op_is_inside_loop(self, op):
 980     """True if op was created inside the pfor loop body."""
 981     assert isinstance(op, ops.Operation)
 982     # Note that we use self._pfor_op_ids for the check and not self._pfor_ops
 983     # since it appears there tensorflow API could return different python
 984     # objects representing the same Operation node.
 985     return op._id in self._pfor_op_ids
 986 
 987   def _convert_sparse(self, y):
 988     """Returns the converted value corresponding to SparseTensor y.
 989 
 990     For SparseTensors, instead of stacking the component tensors separately,
 991     resulting in component tensors with shapes (N, m, rank), (N, m), and (N,
 992     rank) respectively for indices, values, and dense_shape (where N is the loop
 993     length and m is the number of sparse tensor values per loop iter), we want
 994     to logically stack the SparseTensors, to create a SparseTensor whose
 995     components are size (N * m, rank + 1), (N * m, ), and (rank + 1,)
 996     respectively.
 997 
 998     Here, we try to get the conversion of each component tensor.
 999     If the tensors are stacked via a sparse conversion, return the resulting
1000     SparseTensor composed of the converted components. Otherwise, the component
1001     tensors are either unstacked or stacked naively. In the latter case, we
1002     unstack the component tensors to reform loop_len SparseTensor elements,
1003     then correctly batch them.
1004 
1005     The unstacked tensors must have the same rank. Each dimension of each
1006     SparseTensor will expand to be the largest among all SparseTensor elements
1007     for that dimension. For example, if there are N SparseTensors of rank 3
1008     being stacked, with N dense shapes, where the i_th shape is (x_i, y_i, z_i),
1009     the new dense shape will be (N, max_i(x_i), max_i(y_i), max_i(z_i)).
1010 
1011     Args:
1012       y: A tf.SparseTensor.
1013 
1014     Returns:
1015       A tf.SparseTensor that is the converted value corresponding to y.
1016     """
1017     outputs = [
1018         self._convert_helper(t) for t in (y.indices, y.values, y.dense_shape)
1019     ]
1020     assert all(isinstance(o, WrappedTensor) for o in outputs)
1021 
1022     if all(w.is_sparse_stacked for w in outputs):
1023       return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(*[w.t for w in outputs])
1024 
1025     assert not any(w.is_sparse_stacked for w in outputs), (
1026         "Error converting SparseTensor. All components should be logically "
1027         "stacked, or none.")
1028 
1029     # If component tensors were not sparsely stacked, they are either unstacked
1030     # or stacked without knowledge that they are components of sparse tensors.
1031     # In this case, we have to restack them.
1032     return self._restack_sparse_tensor_logically(
1033         *[self._unwrap_or_tile(w) for w in outputs])
1034 
1035   def _restack_sparse_tensor_logically(self, indices, values, shape):
1036     sparse_tensor_rank = indices.get_shape()[-1].value
1037     if sparse_tensor_rank is not None:
1038       sparse_tensor_rank += 1
1039 
1040     def map_fn(args):
1041       res = gen_sparse_ops.serialize_sparse(
1042           args[0], args[1], args[2], out_type=dtypes.variant)
1043       return res
1044 
1045     # Applies a map function to the component tensors to serialize each
1046     # sparse tensor element and batch them all, then deserializes the batch.
1047     # TODO(rachelim): Try to do this without map_fn -- add the right offsets
1048     # to shape and indices tensors instead.
1049     result = functional_ops.map_fn(
1050         map_fn, [indices, values, shape], dtype=dtypes.variant)
1051     return sparse_ops.deserialize_sparse(
1052         result, dtype=values.dtype, rank=sparse_tensor_rank)
1053 
1054   def _unwrap_or_tile(self, wrapped_tensor):
1055     """Given a wrapped tensor, unwrap if stacked. Otherwise, tiles it."""
1056     output, is_stacked = wrapped_tensor.t, wrapped_tensor.is_stacked
1057     if is_stacked:
1058       return output
1059     else:
1060       return _stack(output, self._loop_len_vector).t
1061 
1062   def convert(self, y):
1063     """Returns the converted value corresponding to y.
1064 
1065     Args:
1066       y: A ops.Tensor or a ops.Operation object. If latter, y should not have
1067         any outputs.
1068 
1069     Returns:
1070       If y does not need to be converted, it returns y as is. Else it returns
1071       the "converted value" corresponding to y.
1072     """
1073     if y is None:
1074       return None
1075     if isinstance(y, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor):
1076       return self._convert_sparse(y)
1077     output = self._convert_helper(y)
1078     if isinstance(output, WrappedTensor):
1079       assert isinstance(y, ops.Tensor)
1080       return self._unwrap_or_tile(output)
1081     else:
1082       assert isinstance(y, ops.Operation)
1083       assert not y.outputs
1084       assert isinstance(output, ops.Operation)
1085     return output
1086 
1087   def _was_converted(self, t):
1088     """True if t is not a conversion of itself."""
1089     converted_t = self._conversion_map[t]
1090     return converted_t.t is not t
1091 
1092   def _add_conversion(self, old_output, new_output):
1093     self._conversion_map[old_output] = new_output
1094 
1095   def _convert_helper(self, op_or_tensor):
1096     stack = [op_or_tensor]
1097     while stack:
1098       y = stack[0]
1099       if y in self._conversion_map:
1100         assert isinstance(self._conversion_map[y],
1101                           (WrappedTensor, ops.Operation))
1102         stack.pop(0)
1103         continue
1104       if isinstance(y, ops.Operation):
1105         assert not y.outputs, (
1106             "We only support converting Operation objects with no outputs. "
1107             "Got %s", y)
1108         y_op = y
1109       else:
1110         assert isinstance(y, ops.Tensor), y
1111         y_op = y.op
1112 
1113       is_while_loop = y_op.type == "Exit"
1114       if is_while_loop:
1115         while_op = WhileOp(y, pfor_ops=self._pfor_ops)
1116         is_inside_loop = while_op.is_inside_loop
1117         # If all nodes in the while_loop graph were created inside the pfor, we
1118         # treat the whole loop subgraph as a single op (y_op) and try to convert
1119         # it. For while_loops that are created completely or partially outside,
1120         # we treat them as external and should be able to simply return the Exit
1121         # node output as is without needing any conversion. Note that for
1122         # while_loops that are partially constructed inside, we assume they will
1123         # be loop invariant. If that is not the case, it will create runtime
1124         # errors since the converted graph would depend on the self._loop_var
1125         # placeholder.
1126         if is_inside_loop:
1127           y_op = while_op
1128       else:
1129         is_inside_loop = self.op_is_inside_loop(y_op)
1130 
1131       # If this op was not created inside the loop body, we will return as is.
1132       # 1. Convert inputs and control inputs.
1133 
1134       def _add_to_stack(x):
1135         if x not in self._conversion_map:
1136           stack.insert(0, x)
1137           return True
1138         else:
1139           return False
1140 
1141       if is_inside_loop:
1142         added_to_stack = False
1143         for inp in y_op.inputs:
1144           added_to_stack |= _add_to_stack(inp)
1145         for cinp in y_op.control_inputs:
1146           if cinp.outputs:
1147             for t in cinp.outputs:
1148               added_to_stack |= _add_to_stack(t)
1149           else:
1150             added_to_stack |= _add_to_stack(cinp)
1151         if added_to_stack:
1152           continue
1153 
1154         converted_inputs = [self._conversion_map[inp] for inp in y_op.inputs]
1155         some_input_converted = any(
1156             [self._was_converted(x) for x in y_op.inputs])
1157         some_input_stacked = any([x.is_stacked for x in converted_inputs])
1158 
1159         converted_control_ops = set()
1160         some_control_input_converted = False
1161         for cinp in y_op.control_inputs:
1162           if cinp.outputs:
1163             for t in cinp.outputs:
1164               converted_t = self._conversion_map[t]
1165               if self._was_converted(t):
1166                 some_control_input_converted = True
1167               converted_control_ops.add(converted_t.t.op)
1168           else:
1169             converted_cinp = self._conversion_map[cinp]
1170             assert isinstance(converted_cinp, ops.Operation)
1171             if converted_cinp != cinp:
1172               some_control_input_converted = True
1173             converted_control_ops.add(converted_cinp)
1174         converted_control_ops = list(converted_control_ops)
1175         is_stateful = _is_stateful_pfor_op(y_op)
1176       else:
1177         converted_inputs = []
1178         converted_control_ops = []
1179       logging.vlog(3, "converting op:%s\ninputs:%s\ncontrol_inputs:%s", y_op,
1180                    converted_inputs, converted_control_ops)
1181 
1182       # 2. Convert y_op
1183       # If converting a while_loop, we let the while_loop convertor deal with
1184       # putting the control dependencies appropriately.
1185       control_dependencies = [] if is_while_loop else converted_control_ops
1186       with ops.control_dependencies(control_dependencies), ops.name_scope(
1187           y_op.name + "/pfor/"):
1188         # None of the inputs and control inputs were converted.
1189         if (not is_inside_loop or
1190             (not is_stateful and not some_input_converted and
1191              not some_control_input_converted)):
1192           if y == y_op:
1193             assert not isinstance(y_op, WhileOp)
1194             new_outputs = y_op
1195           else:
1196             new_outputs = [wrap(x, False) for x in y_op.outputs]
1197         elif not (is_stateful or is_while_loop or some_input_stacked):
1198           # All inputs are unstacked or uncoverted but some control inputs are
1199           # converted.
1200           # TODO(rachelim): Handle the case where some inputs are sparsely
1201           # stacked (i.e. any([x.is_sparse_stacked for x in converted_inputs]))
1202           new_op = _create_op(y_op.type, [x.t for x in converted_inputs],
1203                               [x.dtype for x in y_op.outputs],
1204                               y_op.node_def.attr)
1205           if y == y_op:
1206             new_outputs = new_op
1207           else:
1208             new_outputs = [wrap(x, False) for x in new_op.outputs]
1209         else:
1210           # Either some inputs are not loop invariant or op is stateful.
1211           if hasattr(y_op, "pfor_converter"):
1212             converter = y_op.pfor_converter
1213           else:
1214             converter = _pfor_converter_registry.get(y_op.type, None)
1215           if converter is None:
1216             if flags.FLAGS.op_conversion_fallback_to_while_loop:
1217               converter = _fallback_converter
1218             else:
1219               raise ValueError(
1220                   "No converter defined for %s\n%s\ninputs: %s. "
1221                   "\nEither add a converter or set "
1222                   "--op_conversion_fallback_to_while_loop=True, "
1223                   "which may run slower" % (y_op.type, y_op, converted_inputs))
1224           # TODO(rachelim): Handle the case where some inputs are sparsely
1225           # stacked. We should only call the converter if it supports handling
1226           # those inputs.
1227           new_outputs = converter(_PforInput(self, y_op, converted_inputs))
1228           if isinstance(new_outputs, WrappedTensor):
1229             new_outputs = [new_outputs]
1230           assert isinstance(new_outputs,
1231                             (list, tuple, ops.Operation)), new_outputs
1232         logging.vlog(2, "converted %s %s", y_op, new_outputs)
1233 
1234         # Insert into self._conversion_map
1235         if y == y_op:
1236           assert isinstance(new_outputs, ops.Operation)
1237           self._add_conversion(y_op, new_outputs)
1238         else:
1239           for old_output, new_output in zip(y_op.outputs, new_outputs):
1240             assert isinstance(new_output, WrappedTensor), (new_output, y, y_op)
1241             self._add_conversion(old_output, new_output)
1242         stack.pop(0)
1243 
1244     return self._conversion_map[op_or_tensor]
1245

1273 def _flatten_first_two_dims(x):
1274   """Merges first two dimensions."""
1275   old_shape = array_ops.shape(x)
1276   new_shape = array_ops.concat([[-1], old_shape[2:]], axis=0)
1277   return array_ops.reshape(x, new_shape)
1278 
1279 
1280 def _unflatten_first_dim(x, first_dim):
1281   """Splits first dimension into [first_dim, -1]."""
1282   old_shape = array_ops.shape(x)
1283   new_shape = array_ops.concat([first_dim, [-1], old_shape[1:]], axis=0)
1284   return array_ops.reshape(x, new_shape)

1287 def _inputs_with_flattening(pfor_input, input_indices):
1288   """Stacks and flattens first dim of inputs at indices `input_indices`."""
1289   if input_indices is None:
1290     input_indices = []
1291   pfor_input.stack_inputs(stack_indices=input_indices)
1292   inputs = []
1293   for i in range(pfor_input.num_inputs):
1294     if i in input_indices:
1295       inp = pfor_input.stacked_input(i)
1296       inp = _flatten_first_two_dims(inp)
1297     else:
1298       inp = pfor_input.unstacked_input(i)
1299     inputs.append(inp)
1300   return inputs

1303 @RegisterPForWithArgs("Conv2D", dims=[0])

1320 _channel_flatten_input_cache = {}
1321 
1322 
1323 def _channel_flatten_input(x, data_format):
1324   """Merge the stack dimension with the channel dimension.
1325 
1326   If S is pfor's stacking dimension, then,
1327     - for SNCHW, we transpose to NSCHW. If N dimension has size 1, the transpose
1328       should be cheap.
1329     - for SNHWC, we transpose to NHWCS.
1330   We then merge the S and C dimension.
1331 
1332   Args:
1333     x: ops.Tensor to transform.
1334     data_format: "NCHW" or "NHWC".
1335 
1336   Returns:
1337     A 3-element tuple with the transformed value, along with the shape for
1338     reshape and order for transpose required to transform back.
1339   """
1340 
1341   graph = ops.get_default_graph()
1342   cache_key = (graph, x, data_format)
1343   if cache_key not in _channel_flatten_input_cache:
1344     x_shape = array_ops.shape(x)
1345     if data_format == b"NCHW":
1346       order = [1, 0, 2, 3, 4]
1347       shape = array_ops.concat([x_shape[1:2], [-1], x_shape[3:]], axis=0)
1348       reverse_order = order
1349     else:
1350       order = [1, 2, 3, 0, 4]
1351       shape = array_ops.concat([x_shape[1:4], [-1]], axis=0)
1352       reverse_order = [3, 0, 1, 2, 4]
1353     # Move S dimension next to C dimension.
1354     x = array_ops.transpose(x, order)
1355     reverse_shape = array_ops.shape(x)
1356     # Reshape to merge the S and C dimension.
1357     x = array_ops.reshape(x, shape)
1358     outputs = x, reverse_order, reverse_shape
1359     _channel_flatten_input_cache[cache_key] = outputs
1360   else:
1361     outputs = _channel_flatten_input_cache[cache_key]
1362   return outputs

1365 # Note that with training=True, running FusedBatchNorm on individual examples
1366 # is very different from running FusedBatchNorm on a batch of those examples.
1367 # This is because, for the latter case, the operation can be considered as first
1368 # computing the mean and variance over all the examples and then using these
1369 # to scale all those examples. This creates a data dependency between these
1370 # different "iterations" since the inputs to the scaling step depends on the
1371 # statistics coming from all these inputs.
1372 # As with other kernels, the conversion here effectively runs the kernel
1373 # independently for each iteration, and returns outputs by stacking outputs from
1374 # each of those iterations.
1375 @RegisterPFor("FusedBatchNorm")
1376 def _convert_fused_batch_norm(pfor_input):
1377   is_training = pfor_input.get_attr("is_training")
1378   # When BatchNorm is used with training=False, mean and variance are provided
1379   # externally and used as is by the op. Thus, we can merge the S and N
1380   # dimensions as we do for regular operations.
1381   # When BatchNorm is used with training=True, mean and variance are computed
1382   # for each channel across the batch dimension (first one). If we merge S and N
1383   # dimensions, mean and variances will be computed over a larger set. So, we
1384   # merge the S and C dimensions instead.
1385   if not is_training:
1386     # We return zeros for batch_mean and batch_variance output. Note that CPU
1387     # and GPU seem to have different behavior for those two outputs. CPU outputs
1388     # zero because these values are not used during inference. GPU outputs
1389     # something, probably real means and variances.
1390     inputs = _inputs_with_flattening(pfor_input, [0])
1391     outputs = _create_op(
1392         pfor_input.op_type,
1393         inputs, [x.dtype for x in pfor_input.outputs],
1394         attrs=pfor_input.op.node_def.attr).outputs
1395     y = outputs[0]
1396     n = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
1397     y = _unflatten_first_dim(y, n)
1398     mean = pfor_input.unstacked_input(3)
1399     zeros = array_ops.zeros_like(mean)
1400     return [wrap(y, True), wrap(zeros, False), wrap(zeros, False)]
1401 
1402   pfor_input.stack_inputs()
1403   data_format = pfor_input.get_attr("data_format")
1404   # We merge the first dimension with the "C" dimension, run FusedBatchNorm, and
1405   # then transpose back.
1406   x = pfor_input.stacked_input(0)
1407   x, reverse_order, reverse_shape = _channel_flatten_input(x, data_format)
1408   # Note that we stack all the other inputs as well so that they are the same
1409   # size as the new size of the channel dimension.
1410   inputs = [x] + [
1411       array_ops.reshape(pfor_input.stacked_input(i), [-1])
1412       for i in range(1, pfor_input.num_inputs)
1413   ]
1414   outputs = _create_op(
1415       pfor_input.op_type,
1416       inputs, [x.dtype for x in pfor_input.outputs],
1417       attrs=pfor_input.op.node_def.attr).outputs
1418   y = outputs[0]
1419   y = array_ops.reshape(y, reverse_shape)
1420   y = array_ops.transpose(y, reverse_order)
1421   n = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
1422   outputs = [_unflatten_first_dim(x, n) for x in outputs[1:]]
1423   outputs = [y] + outputs
1424   return [wrap(x, True) for x in outputs]

1427 @RegisterPFor("FusedBatchNormGrad")
1428 def _convert_fused_batch_norm_grad(pfor_input):
1429   pfor_input.stack_inputs()
1430   data_format = pfor_input.get_attr("data_format")
1431   y_backprop = pfor_input.stacked_input(0)
1432   y_backprop, _, _ = _channel_flatten_input(y_backprop, data_format)
1433   x = pfor_input.stacked_input(1)
1434   x, x_reverse_order, x_reverse_shape = _channel_flatten_input(x, data_format)
1435   inputs = [y_backprop, x] + [
1436       array_ops.reshape(pfor_input.stacked_input(i), [-1])
1437       for i in range(2, pfor_input.num_inputs)
1438   ]
1439   outputs = _create_op(
1440       pfor_input.op_type,
1441       inputs, [x.dtype for x in pfor_input.outputs],
1442       attrs=pfor_input.op.node_def.attr).outputs
1443   x_backprop = outputs[0]
1444   x_backprop = array_ops.reshape(x_backprop, x_reverse_shape)
1445   x_backprop = array_ops.transpose(x_backprop, x_reverse_order)
1446   n = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
1447   outputs = [_unflatten_first_dim(x, n) for x in outputs[1:]]
1448   outputs = [x_backprop] + outputs
1449   return [wrap(output, True) for output in outputs]

1452 @RegisterPForWithArgs("Conv2DBackpropInput", flatten_dims=[2], shape_dim=0)

1454 def _convert_flatten_batch_shape_input(pfor_input, op_type, flatten_dims,

1471 @RegisterPFor("Conv2DBackpropFilter")
1472 def _convert_conv2d_backprop_filter(pfor_input):
1473   pfor_input.stack_inputs(stack_indices=[2])
1474   inputs, inputs_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(0)
1475   filter_sizes = pfor_input.unstacked_input(1)
1476   grads = pfor_input.stacked_input(2)
1477   strides = pfor_input.get_attr("strides")
1478   padding = pfor_input.get_attr("padding")
1479   use_cudnn_on_gpu = pfor_input.get_attr("use_cudnn_on_gpu")
1480   data_format = pfor_input.get_attr("data_format")
1481   dilations = pfor_input.get_attr("dilations")
1482   if inputs_stacked:
1483     # TODO(agarwal): Implement this efficiently.
1484     logging.warn("Conv2DBackpropFilter uses a while_loop. Fix that!")
1485 
1486     def while_body(i, ta):
1487       inp_i = inputs[i, ...]
1488       grad_i = grads[i, ...]
1489       output = nn_ops.conv2d_backprop_filter(
1490           inp_i,
1491           filter_sizes,
1492           grad_i,
1493           strides=strides,
1494           padding=padding,
1495           use_cudnn_on_gpu=use_cudnn_on_gpu,
1496           data_format=data_format,
1497           dilations=dilations)
1498       return i + 1, ta.write(i, array_ops.expand_dims(output, 0))
1499 
1500     n = array_ops.reshape(pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector, [])
1501     _, ta = control_flow_ops.while_loop(
1502         lambda i, ta: i < n, while_body,
1503         (0, tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(inputs.dtype, n)))
1504     output = ta.concat()
1505     return wrap(output, True)
1506   else:
1507     # We merge the stack dimension with the channel dimension of the gradients
1508     # and pretend we had a larger filter (see change to filter_sizes below).
1509     # Once the filter backprop is computed, we reshape and transpose back
1510     # appropriately.
1511     grads, _, _ = _channel_flatten_input(grads, data_format)
1512     n = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
1513     old_filter_sizes = filter_sizes
1514     filter_sizes *= array_ops.concat([[1, 1, 1], n], axis=0)
1515     output = nn_ops.conv2d_backprop_filter(
1516         inputs,
1517         filter_sizes,
1518         grads,
1519         strides=strides,
1520         padding=padding,
1521         use_cudnn_on_gpu=use_cudnn_on_gpu,
1522         data_format=data_format,
1523         dilations=dilations)
1524     new_filter_shape = array_ops.concat([old_filter_sizes[:3], n, [-1]], axis=0)
1525     output = array_ops.reshape(output, new_filter_shape)
1526     output = array_ops.transpose(output, [3, 0, 1, 2, 4])
1527     return wrap(output, True)

1627 @RegisterPFor("Gather")
1628 @RegisterPFor("GatherV2")
1629 def _convert_gather(pfor_input):
1630   param, param_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(0)
1631   indices, indices_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
1632   op_type = pfor_input.op_type
1633   if op_type == "Gather":
1634     validate_indices = pfor_input.get_attr("validate_indices")
1635     axis = 0
1636   else:
1637     validate_indices = None
1638     axis = pfor_input.unstacked_input(2)
1639     axis_value = tensor_util.constant_value(axis)
1640     if axis_value is not None:
1641       axis = axis_value
1642   if indices_stacked and not param_stacked:
1643     if indices == pfor_input.pfor.all_indices and axis == 0:
1644       param_shape0 = param.shape[0].value
1645       indices_shape0 = indices.shape[0].value
1646       if param_shape0 is not None and indices_shape0 == param_shape0:
1647         # Note that with loops and conditionals, indices may not be contiguous.
1648         # However they will be sorted and unique. So if the shape matches, then
1649         # it must be picking up all the rows of param.
1650         return wrap(param, True)
1651       # TODO(agarwal): use array_ops.slice here.
1652     output = array_ops.gather(
1653         param, indices, validate_indices=validate_indices, axis=axis)
1654     if axis != 0:
1655       axis = control_flow_ops.cond(
1656           axis < 0, lambda: axis + array_ops.rank(param), lambda: axis)
1657       order = array_ops.concat(
1658           [[axis],
1659            math_ops.range(axis),
1660            math_ops.range(axis + 1, array_ops.rank(output))],
1661           axis=0)
1662       output = control_flow_ops.cond(
1663           math_ops.equal(axis, 0), lambda: output,
1664           lambda: array_ops.transpose(output, order))
1665     return wrap(output, True)
1666   if param_stacked:
1667     loop_len_vector = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
1668     pfor_input.stack_inputs(stack_indices=[1])
1669     indices = pfor_input.stacked_input(1)
1670     param_flat = _flatten_first_two_dims(param)
1671 
1672     # Recompute indices to handle stacked param.
1673     indices_offset = math_ops.range(
1674         loop_len_vector[0]) * array_ops.shape(param)[1]
1675     # Reshape indices_offset to allow broadcast addition
1676     ones = array_ops.ones([array_ops.rank(indices) - 1], dtype=dtypes.int32)
1677     new_shape = array_ops.concat([loop_len_vector, ones], axis=0)
1678     indices_offset = array_ops.reshape(indices_offset, new_shape)
1679     indices += indices_offset
1680 
1681     # TODO(agarwal): handle axis != 0. May need to transpose param or
1682     # array_ops.gather_nd.
1683     if isinstance(axis, ops.Tensor):
1684       axis_value = tensor_util.constant_value(axis)
1685     else:
1686       try:
1687         axis_value = int(axis)
1688       except TypeError:
1689         axis_value = None
1690     msg = ("Gather, where indices and param are both loop dependent, currently "
1691            "requires axis=0")
1692     if axis_value is not None and axis_value != 0:
1693       raise ValueError("Error while converting %s. %s. Got axis=%d" %
1694                        (pfor_input.op, msg, axis))
1695     with ops.control_dependencies(
1696         [check_ops.assert_equal(axis, 0, message=msg)]):
1697       output = array_ops.gather(param_flat, indices)
1698     return wrap(output, True)

1712 @RegisterPFor("StridedSlice")
1713 def _convert_strided_slice(pfor_input):
1714   inp = pfor_input.stacked_input(0)
1715   begin = pfor_input.unstacked_input(1)
1716   end = pfor_input.unstacked_input(2)
1717   strides = pfor_input.unstacked_input(3)
1718   begin_mask = pfor_input.get_attr("begin_mask")
1719   end_mask = pfor_input.get_attr("end_mask")
1720   ellipsis_mask = pfor_input.get_attr("ellipsis_mask")
1721   new_axis_mask = pfor_input.get_attr("new_axis_mask")
1722   shrink_axis_mask = pfor_input.get_attr("shrink_axis_mask")
1723 
1724   begin = array_ops.concat([[0], begin], axis=0)
1725   end = array_ops.concat([[0], end], axis=0)
1726   strides = array_ops.concat([[1], strides], axis=0)
1727   begin_mask = begin_mask << 1 | 1
1728   end_mask = end_mask << 1 | 1
1729   ellipsis_mask <<= 1
1730   new_axis_mask <<= 1
1731   shrink_axis_mask <<= 1
1732   return wrap(
1733       array_ops.strided_slice(
1734           inp,
1735           begin,
1736           end,
1737           strides,
1738           begin_mask=begin_mask,
1739           end_mask=end_mask,
1740           ellipsis_mask=ellipsis_mask,
1741           new_axis_mask=new_axis_mask,
1742           shrink_axis_mask=shrink_axis_mask), True)

1784 @RegisterPFor("MatMul")
1785 def _convert_matmul(pfor_input):
1786   # TODO(agarwal): Check if tiling is faster than two transposes.
1787   a, a_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(0)
1788   b, b_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
1789   tr_a = pfor_input.get_attr("transpose_a")
1790   tr_b = pfor_input.get_attr("transpose_b")
1791   if a_stacked and b_stacked:
1792     output = wrap(math_ops.matmul(a, b, adjoint_a=tr_a, adjoint_b=tr_b), True)
1793     return output
1794   elif a_stacked:
1795     if tr_a:
1796       a = array_ops.transpose(a, [0, 2, 1])
1797     if a.shape.is_fully_defined():
1798       x, y, z = a.shape
1799     else:
1800       x, y, z = [
1801           array_ops.reshape(i, [])
1802           for i in array_ops.split(array_ops.shape(a), 3)
1803       ]
1804     a = array_ops.reshape(a, [x * y, z])
1805     prod = math_ops.matmul(a, b, transpose_b=tr_b)
1806     return wrap(array_ops.reshape(prod, [x, y, -1]), True)
1807   else:
1808     assert b_stacked
1809     if tr_b:
1810       perm = [2, 0, 1]
1811       b = array_ops.transpose(b, perm)
1812     else:
1813       # As an optimization, if one of the first two dimensions is 1, then we can
1814       # reshape instead of transpose.
1815       # TODO(agarwal): This check can be done inside Transpose kernel.
1816       b_shape = array_ops.shape(b)
1817       min_dim = math_ops.minimum(b_shape[0], b_shape[1])
1818       perm = control_flow_ops.cond(
1819           math_ops.equal(min_dim, 1), lambda: [0, 1, 2], lambda: [1, 0, 2])
1820       new_shape = array_ops.stack([b_shape[1], b_shape[0], b_shape[2]])
1821       b = array_ops.transpose(b, perm)
1822       b = array_ops.reshape(b, new_shape)
1823 
1824     if b.shape.is_fully_defined():
1825       x, y, z = b.shape
1826     else:
1827       x, y, z = [
1828           array_ops.reshape(i, [])
1829           for i in array_ops.split(array_ops.shape(b), 3)
1830       ]
1831     b = array_ops.reshape(b, [x, y * z])
1832     prod = math_ops.matmul(a, b, transpose_a=tr_a)
1833     prod = array_ops.reshape(prod, [-1, y, z])
1834     prod = array_ops.transpose(prod, [1, 0, 2])
1835     return wrap(prod, True)
1836

1895 @RegisterPFor("UnsortedSegmentSum")
1896 def _convert_unsortedsegmentsum(pfor_input):
1897   data, data_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(0)
1898   # TODO(agarwal): handle unstacked?
1899   segment_ids = pfor_input.stacked_input(1)
1900   # TODO(agarwal): handle stacked?
1901   num_segments = pfor_input.unstacked_input(2)
1902   if not data_stacked:
1903     data = _stack(data, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector).t
1904   segment_shape = array_ops.shape(segment_ids)
1905   n = segment_shape[0]
1906   ones = array_ops.ones_like(segment_shape)[1:]
1907   segment_offset = num_segments * math_ops.range(n)
1908   segment_offset = array_ops.reshape(segment_offset,
1909                                      array_ops.concat([[n], ones], axis=0))
1910   segment_ids += segment_offset
1911   num_segments *= n
1912   output = math_ops.unsorted_segment_sum(data, segment_ids, num_segments)
1913   new_output_shape = array_ops.concat(
1914       [[n, -1], array_ops.shape(output)[1:]], axis=0)
1915   output = array_ops.reshape(output, new_output_shape)
1916   return wrap(output, True)

2070 @RegisterPFor("BiasAddGrad")
2071 def _convert_biasaddgrad(pfor_input):
2072   grad = pfor_input.stacked_input(0)
2073   fmt = pfor_input.get_attr("data_format")

2075     output = math_ops.reduce_sum(grad, axis=[1, 3, 4], keepdims=False)
2076   else:
2077     grad_shape = array_ops.shape(grad)
2078     last_dim_shape = grad_shape[-1]
2079     first_dim_shape = grad_shape[0]
2080     output = array_ops.reshape(grad, [first_dim_shape, -1, last_dim_shape])
2081     output = math_ops.reduce_sum(output, axis=[1], keepdims=False)
2082   return wrap(output, True)

2185 # TensorArray conversion is tricky since we don't support arrays of
2186 # TensorArrays. For converting them, we consider two distinct cases:
2187 #
2188 # 1. The array is constructed outside the pfor call, and read/written inside the
2189 # loop.
2190 # This is an easier case since we don't need to make an array of TensorArrays.
2191 # A correctness requirement is that these parallel iterations shouldn't attempt
2192 # to write to the same location. Hence at conversion time we disallow indices to
2193 # be loop-invariant as that would guarantee a collision. Even if the indices are
2194 # not loop-invariant, they could conflict and that shall trigger runtime errors.
2195 #
2196 # 2. The array is constructed and used entirely inside each pfor iteration.
2197 # For simplicity, here we require that the indices used for write/scatter are
2198 # "unstacked". Otherwise it becomes hard to merge the TensorArrays created in
2199 # different pfor iterations. We consider two sub_cases:
2200 #
2201 # 2a Elements written to the array are "stacked"
2202 # To simulate multiple TensorArrays, we may increase the dimension of each
2203 # element of the array. i.e. the i_th row of the j_th entry of the converted
2204 # TensorArray corresponds to the j_th entry of the TensorArray in the i_th
2205 # pfor iteration.
2206 #
2207 # 2b Elements written to the array are "unstacked"
2208 # In this case we don't increase the dimensions to avoid redundant tiling. Each
2209 # iteration is trying to write the same value. So we convert that to a single
2210 # write.
2211 #
2212 # Here are some tricks used to implement the above:
2213 # - TensorArrayV3 constructor encodes the element shape as an attr. Instead of
2214 # trying to trace whether future writes are stacked or unstacked in order to set
2215 # this attr, we set it to correspond to unknown shape.
2216 # - We use the "flow" output of the different ops to track whether the array
2217 # elements are stacked or unstacked. If a stacked write/scatter is done, we make
2218 # the flow stacked as well.
2219 # - We use some heuristic traversal of the graph to track whether the
2220 # TensorArray handle was created inside or outside the pfor loop.
2221 
2222

2256 def _handle_inside_pfor(pfor_input, handle):
2257   """Returns True if handle was created inside the pfor loop."""
2258   # We use some heuristic to find the original TensorArray creation op.
2259   # The logic should handle the common cases (except cond based subgraphs).
2260   # In theory the user could perform different operations on the handle (like
2261   # Reshape, stack multiple handles, etc) which could break this logic.
2262   # TODO(agarwal): handle Switch/Merge.
2263   while handle.op.type in ("Enter", "Identity"):
2264     handle = handle.op.inputs[0]
2265   if handle.op.type not in [
2266       "TensorArrayV3", "TensorArrayGradV3", "TensorArrayGradWithShape"]:
2267     raise ValueError("Unable to find source for handle %s" % handle)
2268   else:
2269     return pfor_input.pfor.op_is_inside_loop(handle.op)

2278 @RegisterPFor("TensorArrayReadV3")
2279 def _convert_tensor_array_read_v3(pfor_input):
2280   handle = pfor_input.unstacked_input(0)
2281   index, index_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
2282   dtype = pfor_input.get_attr("dtype")
2283   flow, flow_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(2)
2284   if flow_stacked:
2285     flow = _unstack_flow(flow)
2286 
2287   is_inside_pfor = _handle_inside_pfor(pfor_input, pfor_input.op.inputs[0])
2288   if is_inside_pfor:
2289     # Note that if we are inside a control flow construct inside the pfor, and
2290     # only some of the iterations are doing the read (i.e.
2291     # `all_indices_partitioned` is True), then the read operation should only
2292     # return values for the currently active pfor iterations (`all_indices`
2293     # below). Hence, whenever the returned value is stacked (i.e. `flow` is
2294     # stacked), we may need to do an extra gather after reading the values. Also
2295     # note that if `is_inside` is false, then values in the tensor array are
2296     # unstacked. So the check is only needed in this branch.
2297     all_indices = pfor_input.pfor.all_indices
2298     all_indices_partitioned = pfor_input.pfor.all_indices_partitioned
2299     # Note: flow_stacked indicates if values in the TensorArray are stacked or
2300     # not.
2301     if index_stacked:
2302       if flow_stacked:
2303         raise ValueError(
2304             "It looks like TensorArrayReadV3 was called on a TensorArray whose"
2305             " values are not loop-invariant, and the read indices were also"
2306             " not loop invariant. This is currently unsupported.")
2307       value = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_gather_v3(
2308           handle, index, flow, dtype=dtype)
2309       return wrap(value, True)
2310     value = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_read_v3(
2311         handle, index, flow, dtype=dtype)
2312     if flow_stacked and all_indices_partitioned:
2313       value = array_ops.gather(value, all_indices)
2314     return wrap(value, flow_stacked)
2315   # Values in the TensorArray should be unstacked (since different iterations
2316   # couldn't write to the same location). So whether output is stacked or not
2317   # depends on index_stacked.
2318   if index_stacked:
2319     value = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_gather_v3(
2320         handle, index, flow, dtype=dtype)
2321   else:
2322     value = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_read_v3(
2323         handle, index, flow, dtype=dtype)
2324   return wrap(value, index_stacked)
