2327 @RegisterPFor("TensorArrayWriteV3")
2328 def _convert_tensor_array_write_v3(pfor_input):
2329   handle = pfor_input.unstacked_input(0)
2330   index, index_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
2331   value, value_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(2)
2332   flow, flow_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(3)
2333   if value_stacked and pfor_input.pfor.all_indices_partitioned:
2334     # Looks like we are in a control flow in a pfor where not all iterations are
2335     # active now. We don't allow that since that could lead to different indices
2336     # having different shapes which will be hard to merge later.
2337     raise ValueError("Writing non loop invariant values to TensorArray from "
2338                      "inside a while_loop/cond not supported.")
2339   if flow_stacked:
2340     flow = _unstack_flow(flow)
2341   is_inside = _handle_inside_pfor(pfor_input, pfor_input.op.inputs[0])
2342   if is_inside:
2343     if index_stacked:
2344       raise ValueError("Need indices for %s to be loop invariant" % handle)
2345     if not flow_stacked and not value_stacked:
2346       flow_out = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_write_v3(handle, index, value, flow)
2347       return wrap(flow_out, False)
2348     else:
2349       if not value_stacked:
2350         value = _stack(value, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector).t
2351       # TODO(agarwal): Note that if flow is unstacked and value is stacked, then
2352       # this may or may not be a safe situation. flow is unstacked both for a
2353       # freshly created TensorArray, as well as after unstacked values are
2354       # written to it. If it is the latter, then we cannot write a stacked value
2355       # now since that may cause runtime errors due to different shapes in the
2356       # array. At the moment we are not able to handle this gracefully and
2357       # distinguish between the two cases. That would require some heuristic
2358       # traversal of the graph to figure out whether all the writes are
2359       # unstacked or not.
2360       flow_out = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_write_v3(handle, index, value, flow)
2361       return _stack(flow_out, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector)
2362   else:
2363     if not index_stacked:
2364       raise ValueError("Need indices for %s to be not loop invariant" % handle)
2365     # Note that even when index_stacked is true, actual values in index may
2366     # still not be unique. However that will cause runtime error when executing
2367     # the scatter operation below.
2368     if not value_stacked:
2369       value = _stack(value, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector).t
2370     flow_out = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_scatter_v3(handle, index, value, flow)
2371     return _stack(flow_out, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector)

2374 def _transpose_first_two_dims(value):
2375   # TODO(agarwal): optimize if one of the dims == 1.
2376   value_shape = array_ops.shape(value)
2377   v0 = value_shape[0]
2378   v1 = value_shape[1]
2379   value = array_ops.reshape(value, [v0, v1, -1])
2380   value = array_ops.transpose(value, [1, 0, 2])
2381   new_shape = array_ops.concat([[v1, v0], value_shape[2:]], axis=0)
2382   return array_ops.reshape(value, new_shape)

2385 @RegisterPFor("TensorArrayGatherV3")
2386 def _convert_tensor_array_gather_v3(pfor_input):
2387   handle = pfor_input.unstacked_input(0)
2388   indices, indices_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
2389   indices = array_ops.reshape(indices, [-1])
2390   flow, flow_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(2)
2391   if flow_stacked:
2392     flow = _unstack_flow(flow)
2393   dtype = pfor_input.get_attr("dtype")
2394   # TODO(agarwal): support element_shape attr?
2395 
2396   n = pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector
2397   value = data_flow_ops.tensor_array_gather_v3(
2398       handle, indices, flow, dtype=dtype)
2399   is_inside = _handle_inside_pfor(pfor_input, pfor_input.op.inputs[0])
2400   if is_inside:
2401     # flow_stacked indicates if values in the TensorArray are stacked or not.
2402     if indices_stacked:
2403       if flow_stacked:
2404         raise ValueError(
2405             "It looks like TensorArrayGatherV3 was called on a TensorArray "
2406             "whose values are not loop-invariant, and the indices were also "
2407             "not loop invariant. This is currently unsupported.")
2408       else:
2409         value = _unflatten_first_dim(value, n)
2410         return wrap(value, True)
2411     else:
2412       if flow_stacked:
2413         # Since elements in this array are stacked and `value` was produced by
2414         # gather, its first two dims are "gathered elements" and "stack
2415         # dimension". Our semantics require these two to be flipped.
2416         value = _transpose_first_two_dims(value)
2417       return wrap(value, flow_stacked)
2418   else:
2419     # Values in the TensorArray should be unstacked (since different iterations
2420     # couldn't write to the same location). So whether output is stacked or not
2421     # depends on indices_stacked.
2422     if indices_stacked:
2423       value = _unflatten_first_dim(value, n)
2424     return wrap(value, indices_stacked)

2494 # StackV2 conversion is tricky since we don't have arrays of StackV2. So similar
2495 # to TensorArrays, we convert them by changing the dimension of the elements
2496 # inside the stack.
2497 #
2498 # We consider two cases:
2499 #
2500 # 1. StackV2 is constructed and used entirely inside the pfor loop.
2501 # We keep a single Stack and perform the push/pop operations of all the
2502 # iterations in lock-step. We also assume that all the iterations perform these
2503 # operations. In case of dynamic control flow, if only some of the iterations
2504 # try to perform a push/pop, then the conversion may not work correctly and may
2505 # cause undefined behavior.
2506 # TODO(agarwal): test StackV2 with dynamic control flow.
2507 #
2508 # 2. StackV2 is constructed outside the pfor loop.
2509 # Performing stack push/pop in a parallel fashion is ill-defined. However given
2510 # that reading stacks created externally is a common operation when computing
2511 # jacobians, we provide some special semantics here as follows.
2512 #  - disallow push operations to the stack
2513 #  - pop operations are performed in lock step by all iterations, similar to the
2514 #  case when the stack is created inside. A single value is popped during the
2515 #  lock-step operation and broadcast to all the iterations. Values in the stack
2516 #  are assumed to be loop-invariant.
2517 #
2518 # Some other implementation details:
2519 # We use an ugly logic to find whether values in Stack data structure are
2520 # loop invariant or not. When converting push/pop operations, we keep track of
2521 # whether the last conversion used a stacked value or not (see _stack_cache
2522 # below). As a result if an unstacked value is written first, subsequent stacked
2523 # writes are disallowed when they could have been allowed in theory.
2524 
2525 # Map from cache key based on StackV2 handle to a bool indicating whether values
2526 # are stacked or not.
2527 # TODO(agarwal): move _stack_cache inside pfor?
2528 _stack_cache = {}
2529 
2530 
2531 def _stack_cache_key(pfor_input):
2532   """Create cache key corresponding to a stack handle."""
2533   op_type = pfor_input.op_type
2534   assert op_type in ["StackPushV2", "StackPopV2"], op_type
2535   orig_handle = pfor_input.op.inputs[0]
2536   while orig_handle.op.type in ["Identity", "Enter"]:
2537     orig_handle = orig_handle.op.inputs[0]
2538   assert orig_handle.op.type == "StackV2", orig_handle.op
2539   return ops.get_default_graph(), pfor_input.pfor, orig_handle
2540 
2541 
2542 def _stack_handle_inside_pfor(handle, pfor_input):
2543   while handle.op.type in ["Identity", "Enter"]:
2544     handle = handle.op.inputs[0]
2545   assert handle.op.type == "StackV2", (
2546       "Unable to find StackV2 op. Got %s" % handle.op)
2547   return pfor_input.pfor.op_is_inside_loop(handle.op)
2548

2550 @RegisterPFor("StackPushV2")
2551 def _convert_stack_push_v2(pfor_input):
2552   handle = pfor_input.unstacked_input(0)
2553   elem, elem_stacked, _ = pfor_input.input(1)
2554   swap_memory = pfor_input.get_attr("swap_memory")
2555 
2556   if not _stack_handle_inside_pfor(pfor_input.op.inputs[0], pfor_input):
2557     raise ValueError("StackPushV2 not allowed on stacks created outside pfor")
2558   stack_cache_key = _stack_cache_key(pfor_input)
2559   stacked = _stack_cache.get(stack_cache_key, None)
2560   if stacked is None:
2561     stacked = elem_stacked
2562     _stack_cache[stack_cache_key] = stacked
2563   else:
2564     # If we previously made it unstacked then we can't revert to being stacked.
2565     if not stacked and elem_stacked:
2566       raise ValueError(
2567           "It looks like the stack was previously determined to be loop"
2568           " invariant, but we are now trying to push a loop dependent value"
2569           " to it. This is currently unsupported.")
2570     if stacked and not elem_stacked:
2571       elem = _stack(elem, pfor_input.pfor.loop_len_vector).t
2572   out = data_flow_ops.stack_push_v2(handle, elem, swap_memory=swap_memory)
2573   return wrap(out, stacked)
2574 
2575 
2576 # Note that inputs to this convertor will be unstacked. However it should get
2577 # called since it is a stateful op.
2578 @RegisterPFor("StackPopV2")
2579 def _convert_stack_pop_v2(pfor_input):
2580   handle = pfor_input.unstacked_input(0)
2581   stack_cache_key = _stack_cache_key(pfor_input)
2582   stacked = _stack_cache.get(stack_cache_key, None)
2583   # If a StackPushV2 has not been converted yet, we default to unstacked since
2584   # the push could be outside of pfor, or the covertor may not be called if the
2585   # inputs are unconverted.
2586   if stacked is None:
2587     stacked = False
2588     _stack_cache[stack_cache_key] = False
2589   elem_type = pfor_input.get_attr("elem_type")
2590   out = data_flow_ops.stack_pop_v2(handle, elem_type)
2591   return wrap(out, stacked)
